description._content: Took this from just inside the gate of the Army Firing Range, hence the title.  From the top of Castlelaw Hill  looking over to Turnhouse, Carnethy, Scald Law, East and West Kip Hills with the reservoirs of Glencorse and Loganlea nestling at the bottom.
This is from Allermuir Hill in  the Pentlands looking over to Castlelaw Hill and beyond with Turnhouse, Carnethy, Scald Law, East and West Kip Hills all visible.

description._content: Taken from the walls of Edinburgh Castle, overlooking a good portion of the city.  Just next to the roofline, you can see a tower on the hill along with some columns. description._content: This time with the warm treatment...

Carmen Capaldi photographed at Edinburgh's Portobello Beach. This is the promotional image for International Waters, the new show from David Leddy. Premiering later this month at the Tron Theatre in Glasgow, it moves thereafter to Edinburgh, Aberdeen and Inverness. Details at www.davidleddy.com/shows/international-waters "The social fabric has finally torn. Airports are closed, roads are blocked. Now even the 1% need to seek asylum. Four obscenely rich members of the elite pay through the nose to join an exclusive party on the last ship leaving London. They stay alive using the only things they know – money, sex and madness. But the ship is sailing in the wrong direction. They don’t know each other. They don’t know the Captain. They don’t know what the hell is going on. Like a perverse Aesop’s fable for the apocalypse, the twisting plot explores how progress can sometimes be a trap. In this case it involves elegant glamour, brutal food poisoning, cyborg finance, and a delicious bull testicle meringue." Edinburgh, 2015. Website | Twitter | Facebook | Tumblr | Instagram

Another view from Calton Hill in Edinburgh, looking out, westwards, upriver on the Firth of Forth towards the two bridges, the 60s suspension road bridge and the 19th century marvel of engineering that is the mighty Forth Rail Bridge, the distinctive diamond shape of the cantilever construction rising like the humps of a fabled sea monster. 

And now joined by a third bridge, the new Queensferry Crossing, still under construction, but you can see the huge pillars rising alongside the existing 19th and 20th century bridges here. It will supplement the 1960s road bridge, which has found a corrosion problem with sea air getting into the massive cables, a problem which has now been discovered in many suspension bridges around the world, although innovative new techniques are being used on the old suspension bridge to treat and arrest the corrosion, so it may well still be active even when the new one comes onstream.
The forth road bridge with the rail bridge in the background.

Another view from Calton Hill in Edinburgh, looking north across the Firth of Forth - in the foreground some modern apartments built around the regenerated harbour area in Leith, across the river the coastline of Fife, and in the river a visitor from the North Sea, a large oil rig.
Lexie at Portobello beach after running about in the sea.
